# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: affine-types
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:affine-types/affine-logic] The name "affine logic" is associated with linear logic, to which it differs by allowing the weakening rule.
[src:affine-types/affine-logic] Jean-Yves Girard introduced the name as part of the geometry of interaction semantics of linear logic, which characterizes linear logic in terms of linear algebra; here he alludes to affine transformations on vector spaces.
[src:affine-types/affine-logic] Grishin used this logic in 1974, after observing that Russell's paradox cannot be derived in a set theory without contraction, even with an unbounded comprehension axiom.
[src:affine-types/affine-logic] Likewise, the logic formed the basis of a decidable sub-theory of predicate logic, called 'Direct logic' (Ketonen & Wehrauch, 1984; Ketonen & Bellin, 1989).
[src:affine-types/affine-logic] Affine logic can be embedded into linear logic by rewriting the affine arrow $A\rightarrow B$ as the linear arrow $A\multimap B\otimes \top$ .
[src:affine-types/affine-logic] Whereas full linear logic (i.e. propositional linear logic with multiplicatives, additives, and exponentials) is undecidable, full affine logic is decidable.
[src:affine-types/affine-logic] Affine logic forms the foundation of ludics.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] In compiler optimization, **escape analysis** is a method for determining the dynamic scope of pointers – where in the program a pointer can be accessed.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] It is related to pointer analysis and shape analysis.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] When a variable (or an object) is allocated in a subroutine, a pointer to the variable can *escape* to other threads of execution, or to calling subroutines.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] If an implementation uses tail call optimization (usually required for functional languages), objects may also be seen as escaping to *called* subroutines.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] If a language supports first-class continuations (as do Scheme and Standard ML of New Jersey), portions of the call stack may also escape.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] If a subroutine allocates an object and returns a pointer to it, the object can be accessed from undetermined places in the program – the pointer has "escaped".
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] Pointers can also escape if they are stored in global variables or other data structures that, in turn, escape the current procedure.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] Escape analysis determines all the places where a pointer can be stored and whether the lifetime of the pointer can be proven to be restricted only to the current procedure and/or thread.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] In object-oriented programming languages, dynamic compilers are particularly good candidates for performing escape analysis.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] In traditional static compilation, method overriding can make escape analysis impossible, as any called method might be overridden by a version that allows a pointer to escape.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] Dynamic compilers can perform escape analysis using the available information on overloading, and re-do the analysis when relevant methods are overridden by dynamic code loading.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] The popularity of the Java programming language has made escape analysis a target of interest.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] Java's combination of heap-only object allocation, built-in threading, the Sun HotSpot dynamic compiler, and OpenJ9's just-in-time compiler (JIT) creates a candidate platform for escape analysis related optimizations (see Escape analysis in Java).
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] Escape analysis is implemented in Java Standard Edition 6.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] Some JVMs support a stronger variant of escape analysis called *partial escape analysis* that makes scalar replacement of an allocated object possible even if the object escapes in some paths of a function.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] In this example, two objects are created (commented with alloc), and one of them is given as an argument to a method of another.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] The method `setFoo()` stores a reference to a received Foo object.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] If the Bar object was on the heap then the reference to Foo would escape.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] But in this case a compiler can determine, with escape analysis, that the Bar object itself does not escape the invocation of `example()`.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] As a result, the reference to Foo cannot escape either, and the compiler can safely allocate both objects on the stack.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] In the following example, the vector *p* does not escape into *g*, so it can be allocated on the stack and then removed from the stack before calling *g*.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] then either *p* would need to be allocated on the heap or (if *g* is known to the compiler when *f* is compiled, and behaves well) allocated on the stack in such a fashion that it can remain in place when *g* is called.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] If continuations are used to implement exception-like control structures, escape analysis can often detect this to avoid having to actually allocate a continuation and copy the call stack into it.
[src:affine-types/escape-analysis] escape analysis will determine that the continuation captured by *call/cc* doesn't escape, so no continuation structure needs to be allocated, and invoking the continuation by calling *continuation* can be implemented by unwinding the stack.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:affine-types/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In object-oriented programming (OOP), **object lifetime** is the period of time between an object's creation and its destruction.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In some programming contexts, object lifetime coincides with the lifetime of a variable that represents the object.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In other contexts – where the object is accessed by reference – object lifetime is not determined by the lifetime of a variable.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] For example, destruction of the variable may only destroy the reference, not the referenced object.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Creation of an object is generally *deterministic*, but destruction varies by programming context.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Some contexts allow for deterministic destruction, but some do not.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Notably, in a garbage-collection environment, objects are destroyed when the garbage collector chooses.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] The syntax for creation and destruction varies by programming context.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In many contexts, including C++, C# and Java, an object is created via special syntax like `new *typename()*`.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In C++, that provides manual memory management, an object is destroyed via the `delete` keyword.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In C# and Java, with no explicit destruction syntax, the garbage collector destroys unused objects automatically.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] An alternative and deterministic approach to automatic destruction is where the object is destroyed when code decrements the object's reference count to zero.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] With an object pool, where objects may be created ahead of time and reused, the apparent creation and destruction of an object may not correspond to actual.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] The pool provides reinitialization for creation and finalization for destruction.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Both creation and destruction may be non-deterministic.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Objects with static memory allocation have a lifetime that coincides with the run of a program, but the *order* of creation and destruction of the various static objects is generally non-deterministic.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Object **life cycle** refers to the events that an object experiences including and between creation and destruction.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Life cycle generally includes memory management and operations after allocation and before deallocation.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Object creation generally consists of *memory allocation* and *initialization* where initialization includes assigning values to fields and running initialization code.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Object destruction generally consists of *finalization* (a.k.a. cleanup) and *memory deallocation* (a.k.a. free).
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] These steps generally proceed in order as: allocate, initialize, finalize, deallocate.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Based on programming context, these steps may be partially or fully automated, and some of the steps can be customized.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] The frequency of customization tends to vary by step and programming context.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Initialization is the most commonly customized step.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Finalization is common in languages with deterministic destruction, notably C++, but rare in garbage-collected languages.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Allocation is rarely customized, and deallocation generally cannot be customized.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] The way to create objects varies across programming contexts.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In some class-based languages, a *constructor* handles initialization.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Like other methods, a constructor can be overloaded in order to support creating with different initial state.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Generally, an object is removed from memory after it is no longer needed.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] However, if there is sufficient memory or a program has a short run time, object destruction may not occur, memory simply being deallocated at process termination.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In some cases, object destruction consists solely of deallocating memory, particularly with garbage-collection, or if the object is a plain old data structure.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In other cases, cleanup is performed prior to deallocation, particularly destroying member objects (in manual memory management), or deleting references from the object to other objects to decrement reference counts (in reference counting).
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] This may be automatic, or a special destruction method may be called on the object.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In class-based languages with deterministic object lifetime, notably C++, a *destructor* is called when an instance is deleted, before the memory is deallocated.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In C++, destructors differ from constructors in various ways.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] They cannot be overloaded, must have no arguments, need not maintain class invariants, and can cause program termination if they throw exceptions.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] With garbage collection, objects may be destroyed when they can no longer be accessed by the program.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] The garbage-collector calls a *finalizer* before memory deallocation.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Destroying an object will cause any references to the object to become invalid.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] With manual memory management, any existing reference becomes a dangling reference.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] With garbage collection, objects are only destroyed when there are no references to them.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Object lifetime begins when allocation completes and ends when deallocation starts.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Thus, during initialization and finalization, an object is alive, but may not be in a consistent state.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] The period between when initialization completes to when finalization starts is when the object is both alive and in a consistent state.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] If creation or destruction fail, error reporting (for example, raising an exception) can be complicated since the object or related objects may be in an inconsistent state.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] For a static variable, with lifespan coinciding with the program run, a creation or destruction error is problematic since program execution is before or after normal execution.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In class-based programming, object creation is also known as *instantiation* (creating an *instance* of a *class*).
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Creation and destruction can be customized via a *constructor* and a *destructor* and sometimes with separate *initializer* and *finalizer* methods.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Notably, a constructor is a class method as there is no object (instance) available until the object is created, but destructors, initializers, and finalizers are instance methods.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Further, constructors and initializers often can accept arguments, while destructors and finalizers generally do not as they are often implicitly callable.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In languages with deterministic lifetime objects, lifetime may be used to piggyback resource management.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] This is called the Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII) idiom.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Resources are acquired during initialization, and released during finalization.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In languages with non-deterministic lifetime objects (i.e. garbage collected), the management of memory is generally kept separate from management of other resources.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] When declared in an automatic context, the object is destroyed at the close of the block it is declared.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] When created dynamically, it lives until it is explicitly destroyed.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] When using smart pointers, its destruction semantics are controlled based on scope or shared references.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] `new Foo()`) it lives until it has no references and the garbage collector deletes it.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] Rust uses lifetime annotations to declare the lifetime of arguments passed into a function.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] The lifetime is declared in the function signature within angle brackets.
[src:affine-types/object-lifetime] In this example a reference to the struct File is passed into the example function with the lifetime annotation 'a.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII is associated most prominently with C++, where it originated, but also Ada, Vala, and Rust.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The technique was developed for exception-safe resource management in C++ during 1984–1989, primarily by Bjarne Stroustrup and Andrew Koenig, and the term itself was coined by Stroustrup.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Other names for this idiom include *Constructor Acquires, Destructor Releases* (CADRe) and one particular style of use is called *Scope-based Resource Management* (SBRM).
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This latter term is for the special case of automatic variables.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII ties resources to object *lifetime,* which may not coincide with entry and exit of a scope.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] (Notably variables allocated on the free store have lifetimes unrelated to any given scope.) However, using RAII for automatic variables (SBRM) is the most common use case.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This code is exception-safe because C++ guarantees that all objects with automatic storage duration (local variables) are destroyed at the end of the enclosing scope in the reverse order of their construction.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The destructors of both the *lock* and *file* objects are therefore guaranteed to be called when returning from the function, whether an exception has been thrown or not.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Local variables allow easy management of multiple resources within a single function: they are destroyed in the reverse order of their construction, and an object is destroyed only if fully constructed—that is, if no exception propagates from its constructor.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Using RAII greatly simplifies resource management, reduces overall code size and helps ensure program correctness.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII is therefore recommended by industry-standard guidelines, and most of the C++ standard library follows the idiom.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The advantages of RAII as a resource management technique are that it provides encapsulation, exception safety (for stack resources), and locality (it allows acquisition and release logic to be written next to each other).
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Encapsulation is provided because resource management logic is defined once in the class, not at each call site.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Finally, locality of definition is provided by writing the constructor and destructor definitions next to each other in the class definition.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Resource management therefore needs to be tied to the lifespan of suitable objects in order to gain automatic allocation and reclamation.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Resources are acquired during initialization, when there is no chance of them being used before they are available, and released with the destruction of the same objects, which is guaranteed to take place even in case of errors.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] As a class invariant, RAII provides guarantees that an object instance that is supposed to have acquired a resource has in fact done so.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The RAII design is often used for controlling mutex locks in multi-threaded applications.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In that use, the object releases the lock when destroyed.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Without RAII in this scenario the potential for deadlock would be high and the logic to lock the mutex would be far from the logic to unlock it.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] With RAII, the code that locks the mutex essentially includes the logic that the lock will be released when execution leaves the scope of the RAII object.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Another typical example is interacting with files: We could have an object that represents a file that is open for writing, wherein the file is opened in the constructor and closed when execution leaves the object's scope.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In both cases, RAII ensures only that the resource in question is released appropriately; care must still be taken to maintain exception safety.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] If the code modifying the data structure or file is not exception-safe, the mutex could be unlocked or the file closed with the data structure or file corrupted.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Ownership of dynamically allocated objects (memory allocated with `new` in C++) can also be controlled with RAII, such that the object is released when the RAII (stack-based) object is destroyed.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] For this purpose, the C++11 standard library defines the smart pointer classes `std::unique_ptr` for single-owned objects and `std::shared_ptr` for objects with shared ownership.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Similar classes are also available through `std::auto_ptr` in C++98, and `boost::shared_ptr` in the Boost libraries.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Also, messages can be sent to network resources using RAII.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In this case, the RAII object would send a message to a socket at the end of the constructor, when its initialization is completed.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] It would also send a message at the beginning of the destructor, when the object is about to be destroyed.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Such a construct might be used in a client object to establish a connection with a server running in another process.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In many languages that lack direct memory management or discourage its use, a similar mechanism called the "dispose pattern" is used to call a `dispose` method that performs relevant resource cleanup on the object at the end of scope.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] For versions of C prior to the introduction of `defer` Clang and the GNU Compiler Collection implement a `[[gnu::cleanup]]` attribute as a non-standard extension to C.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In this example, the compiler arranges for the `fclosep` function to be called on `logFile` before `writeLogFile` returns.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In C++, disposing is done directly with a destructor.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In C++, a class `X` will automatically call its destructor `~X()` when it reaches the end of scope.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The dispose pattern is essentially equivalent to RAII in C++.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] C# features a `using`-with-resources block, which can be used if the object implements `System.IDisposable`.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] It will call a `Dispose()` method at the end of the resource.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Java features a `try`-with-resources block, which can be used if the object implements `java.lang.AutoCloseable`.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] It will call a `close()` method at the end of the resource.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Python features a `with` block, which can be used if the object implements `__enter__` and `__exit__` methods.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This is also used for managing resources such as locks.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Rust allows defining custom cleanup logic, if an object implements `std::ops::Drop`, which will call a `drop()` method after the object leaves scope.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This can also be manually called by `std::mem::drop()`.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII only works for resources acquired and released (directly or indirectly) by stack-allocated objects, where there *is* a well-defined static object lifetime.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Heap-allocated objects which themselves acquire and release resources are common in many languages, including C++.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII depends on heap-based objects to be implicitly or explicitly deleted along all possible execution paths, in order to trigger its resource-releasing destructor (or equivalent).
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This can be achieved by using smart pointers to manage all heap objects, with weak pointers for cyclically referenced objects.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In C++, stack unwinding is only guaranteed to occur if the exception is caught somewhere.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This is because "If no matching handler is found in a program, the function terminate() is called; whether or not the stack is unwound before this call to terminate() is implementation-defined (15.5.1)." (C++03 standard, §15.3/9).
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This behavior is usually acceptable, since the operating system releases remaining resources like memory, files, sockets, etc. at program termination.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] At the 2018 Gamelab conference, Jonathan Blow claimed that use of RAII can cause memory fragmentation which in turn can cause cache misses and a 100 times or worse hit on performance.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Perl, Python (in the CPython implementation), and PHP manage object lifetime by reference counting, which makes it possible to use RAII.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Objects that are no longer referenced are immediately destroyed or finalized and released, so a destructor or finalizer can release the resource at that time.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] However, it is not always idiomatic in such languages, and is specifically discouraged in Python (in favor of context managers and *finalizers* from the *weakref* package).
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] However, object lifetimes are not necessarily bound to any scope, and objects may be destroyed non-deterministically or not at all.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This makes it possible to accidentally leak resources that should have been released at the end of some scope.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Objects stored in a static variable (notably a global variable) may not be finalized when the program terminates, so their resources are not released; CPython makes no guarantee of finalizing such objects, for instance.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Further, objects with circular references will not be collected by a simple reference counter, and will live indeterminately long; even if collected (by more sophisticated garbage collection), destruction time and destruction order will be non-deterministic.
[src:affine-types/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In CPython there is a cycle detector which detects cycles and finalizes the objects in the cycle, though prior to CPython 3.4, cycles are not collected if any object in the cycle has a finalizer.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] In logic, a **substructural logic** is a logic lacking one of the usual structural rules (e.g. of classical and intuitionistic logic), such as weakening, contraction, exchange or associativity.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] Two of the more significant substructural logics are relevance logic and linear logic.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] Here the structural rules are rules for rewriting the LHS of the sequent, denoted Γ, initially conceived of as a finite string (sequence) of propositions.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] Here we are taking the RHS Σ to be a single proposition *C* (which is the intuitionistic style of sequent); but everything applies equally to the general case, since all the manipulations are taking place to the left of the turnstile symbol $\vdash$ .
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] Linear logic, in which duplicated hypotheses 'count' differently from single occurrences, leaves out both of these rules, while relevant (or relevance) logics merely leaves out the latter rule, on the ground that *B* is clearly irrelevant to the conclusion.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] The above are basic examples of structural rules.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] It is not that these rules are contentious, when applied in conventional propositional calculus.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] They occur naturally in proof theory, and were first noticed there (before receiving a name).
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] There are numerous ways to compose premises (and in the multiple-conclusion case, conclusions as well).
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] But since e.g. {a,a} = {a} we have contraction for free if premises are sets.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] We also have associativity and permutation (or commutativity) for free as well, among other properties.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] In substructural logics, typically premises are not composed into sets, but rather they are composed into more fine-grained structures, such as trees or multisets (sets that distinguish multiple occurrences of elements) or sequences of formulae.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] For example, in linear logic, since contraction fails, the premises must be composed in something at least as fine-grained as multisets.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] Substructural logic is a relatively young field.
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] The first conference on the topic was held in October 1990 in Tübingen, as "Logics with Restricted Structural Rules".
[src:affine-types/substructural-logic] During the conference, Kosta Došen proposed the term "substructural logics", which is now in use today.
